text:
A quick recount of everyone and their goals (mostly for myself. I am bored - this is really my first TTRPG but I love story analysis, please correct any inaccuracies/missing information in the replies):

Current Party (Core):

Tiara
- Definitely takes a lot of the lead. Is probably a lot more utile than people think, as the addition of Animal Ken + an eyes-in-the-sky companion is a good recipe for reconnaissance.

Yuul B. Alwright
- More passive, and will probably take a back seat. A medic character, which is good for Tiara and Scout, who are both more active.

Watoto
- Similar to Yuul. Watoto provides utility in their unique potion blends, though seemingly to a more mystical effect rather than healing. Looks to be a less combat, more roleplay intensive character, with their deal making and stealthy escapes.

Scout
- Like Tiara, very driven and focused. Utility consists of the ability to forge weapons. Along with Tiara, they are the brawn that fulfils the wishes of the brain (the weaker characters, Yuul and Watoto).

Current Party (Extended - basically everyone at the bar as of the end of the livestream):

Uhu (affiliated with Tiara)
Unnamed crow (affiliated with Tiara)
Unnamed woman ("affiliated" with Tiara, possibly a recruiter of sorts)
Victor (affiliated with Tiara and Yuul)
Guard dogs [x3] (affiliated with Watoto)
Unnamed young dealer (affiliated with Watoto)
Unnamed elder lady (affiliated with Watoto)
Unnamed younger sister (affiliated with Scout)
Dr. Nice (first name pending, affiliated with Scout)




Goals for the core party (does not include the overarching goal of saving Mythton from a slew of supernatural creatures):

Tiara: Keep her phoenix pendant safe and protected; Find lost brother
Yuul: Nothing (that I can think of, tbh)
Watoto: Potentially save mother and father; Dismantle the system
Scout: Find mother and father

Side NPC's to potentially watch out for moving forward:


The tall figure stalking Tiara (ambiguous on whether it's a friend or foe)
The coven of creatures (attacked Tiara, definitely a villain type)
Chad (essentially the rest of the Bro Hood, including Nita Frenned, it feels like they'll have interactions with members of the party from here on out)
Aima (considering that we never learnt this character's last name in a tutorial where the surnames often revealed character traits of the agent, I'm getting uneasy vibes from this character and their relation in the story. Especially with their discussion about magic to Yuul)
Unnamed hooked apparition (attacked Yuul, may appear again since Yuul never really subdued it, simply ran)

"The Wyrm" (made a deal with Watoto, this will 100% be brought up again at a point during the adventure)
The Sniper in the Car (also unsure if this is friendly or someone to beware, attacked facility guards, so probably not the nicest - I was half asleep during Ame's tutorial I won't lie)
Mr. Crinkle (probs not, but if Calli wants to make a point with him...)
Paw and Maw (criminals on the run, will probably wish to avoid Scout)

That's about it for all that could be explained within these four tutorials. I am soooo hyped for when the character sheets get reworked. Everyone put so much effort in, it's mind boggling. Honestly, this team is quite the team of artists, lol.

You only have testimony of one very shocked witness and who knows what exactly they saw in that mine? You know, those old caves can have all sorts of gases accumulating in there: sulfur, arsenic, CO2, methane, cow farts. All sorts of nastiness down there. Who can tell what you might see after breathing in that stuff for a good while, let alone licking walls! How do you know there even was a murder? Maybe ol' Betsy was just taking a midnight stroll around the farm and accidentally fell into the well? That can happen. She fell, broke her leg and tried to phone for help but the reception in the mine was so poor that she couldn't get a word out. Totally plausible. Damage on the body? - Critters. Damned rats! Underground piranhas is what they are, totally. 
And where is the body anyway? How can you prove that it actually is Betsy and not some deer Doc mistook for a person in the dark? Maybe ma and pa took ol' Betsy to a nursing home or an 24-hour ice cream parlor. I don't know which country you're from, Sheriff, but in Murica it is innocent until proven guilty and you ain't got even the most circumstancial evidence! No, moider weapen, no blood stains, no DNA or signs of struggle. Nope. I don't see this holding up in a court of law. Perversion of justice is what it is.

text:
Very fun session 😊

Since it's a tutorial, I'm giving some personnal feedbacks. But I'll be honest, there isn't much to say, since this session was excellent.

_
About Gura,

Gura's proactive roleplay complements well with Calli's descriptions/dialogues. It makes a very nice and lively story/adventure, one you can almost experience as if beside the characters. 
Proactive roleplay also relieves Calli from narrating ALL the details. It might even have given her more ideas during the adventure.
However, there are two small drawbacks to this.

1) Adding roleplay lengthens the session. 
Usually, it doesn't matter, but it's still something to keep in mind.
The effect gets even stronger the more people there are (from personnal experience).

If that's ever needed, Calli might need to shorten the sessions if it gets too long, one way or another. 
Or add some event that forces the hand of the players (so that they don't take too much time roleplaying). 
Or simply play longer sessions, if that's a viable option for everyone.

For this sessions, it wasn't really a problem (not a all actually). And I'd take that proactive roleplay anytime anyway.

2) Watch out to not step away from the character's influence.
What it means is that the characters cannot decide what happens in the story, aside from their own actions.
They cannot say "Well the monster is too far anyway" or "Good thing it's still daytime" or even "Well no one is home at this time". 
They can suggest it, and the GM might agree (or not). But it's ultimately the GM's decision.
Better examples would be "Well if the monster is far enough..." or "I check if the sun is still visible" or even "Usually at this time, no one is home".
Those examples let the GM make the final decision, wether the monster is actually far or not, wether the sun is visible or not, or wether the home is empty/seemingly empty/visibly not empty.
(The most extreme bad example would be "Oh boi, [character] is lucky to have his birthday today, especially since their parents always give him some excellent weapons and equipment for their birthday ;) ;)". In that case, the GM has to take the wheel and cancel what the player asserts).

Gura was almost perfect at this. 
New doctor in town ? "People always leave Bellbuckle, they never come back in" (+suspicious of the doctor)
Gossip about family ? "Eh, it's none of their business anyway".
Papa walks in at the forge ? "Heeeey how's't going ?" (interaction immediatly indicates the relationship. She could have said "'mornin 'pa..." or anything else)

What she added was mostly about how her character interacted with NPC that Calli introduced, or how her character feels about some situations, or added some details on the background Calli introduced.
The only time I could detect i happened was during the "blood smell" ( 2:32:15 ) story, in the mine. The story would have been fine if it hadn't any influence on what was currently happening. (To be honest, it wasn't that bad, Calli reestablished the story nicely)

Again, this whole "2)" was not really a problem here. Just something to keep in mind : if you want to add to the story (or complement it), make sure you stay in your character's general influence (or, rather, nothing that influences the general story or the other characters).

(and I repeat : despite those small drawbacks, I'd still take that proactive roleplay anytime, it's so much more pleasant)

__

About Calli,

... I can't see anything that might be considered a problem, or even something to keep in mind for the future.

... Maybe "Make sure to keep an eye on the character's weaknesses/flaws, just in case" ? 
It's not even a problem, it's the players' responsibility.
... Maybe "Keep track of time, and don't let player take too much time doing roleplay : story must progress" ? 
That's assuming each session will have a "beginning" and a "end". It held true for tutorials but future sessions might be ended whenever Calli feels like it. Thus, "too long" sessions might not even exist in the future.
... Maybe "watch out for dice roll, you made one or two errors !" ? 
But it'll be on the players from now on anyway so...

No, really, I can't find anything truly worth mentioning for Calli. 
Excellent job.

__

Again, great session. 😊
We could feel the atmosphere of the South, the intimidation on the Doc, the anxiety from the Sus, and the dread of the walls of... flesh(?)

text:
First off i will identify the general kinds of people in a tabletop rpg

The gamemaster runs the game, tells the story, roleplays the npc's and keeps the game flowing with the players
Hence why they are called game masters

Now for players, which im guessing is you if ever you want to try
You roleplay as your character and before that you make said character and maybe do some bit of study in the particular tabeltop rpg you want to play
Such as the player's handbook for dungeons and dragons 5th edition

Tabletop rpg's are a social game where its all about story telling and roleplaying
Where you get to take part of the wonderful world your gamemaster has created 

Now they are like video game rpg's but you do more than just straightforward quests or looting or combat
You solve exploration and social stuff too
Something a video game cant do since they are limited by code
Speaking of code
The combat itself involves enemies that may be smarter than your typical scripted code enemies as they are also roleplayed and managed by the game master so you, the players, get challenged in one of several ways

You have to try it yourself to get what i mean
Or if ever look for dungeons and dragons 5e guides from Dont Stop Thinking on youtube
Super super easy to understand
You can even try the Dungeon Dudes who cover many easy to understand topics for dungeons and dragons 5e
